The Trustees of the National Railroad Retirement Investment Trust ("the Trust") wish to
establish formal guidelines on reimbursement to the Trustees for expenses incurred in relation to
their duties as Trustees. Accordingly, the following guidelines are hereby adopted as the basis
for reimbursement of expenses incurred by the Trustees on behalf of the Trust.
1. "Reimbursable expenses" shall mean reasonable, proper and necessary expenses
actually incurred in connection with the performance of the duties of a Trustee on
behalf of the Trust, including (a) attendance at scheduled meetings of the Trust, (b)
participation in other meetings on Trust business, and (c) participation in conferences
and seminars on topics relevant to Trust business where such participation has been
previously approved by the Board of Trustees and a certificate of attendance is
2. "Reimbursable expenses" shall not include expenses of a personal nature or those
expenses not directly related to Trust business. Personal recreational and/or
entertainment expenses, or expenses incurred by or on behalf of a spouse or other
person traveling with the Trustee, are not "reimbursable expenses."
3. "Reimbursable expenses" shall include expenditures paid by one Trustee on behalf of
another, if such expenditures would have been reimbursable to the Trustee incurring
4. "Reimbursable expenses" may be incurred during one day traveling to and one day
traveling from a "meeting," and while in attendance at a meeting. Furthermore, an
additional day of expenses may be reimbursed for a trip where doing so results in a
net savings to the Trust for the overall cost of the trip due to the availability of special
airfares, which may be subject to certain restrictive requirements (e.g., Saturday night
5. Reimbursement of expenses can be made to the Trustee directly, or to the employer
of the Trustee in cases where the expense (e.g., airfare) had been charged to, or
"Reimbursable expenses" shall be paid by the Trust upon submission of an expense
statement in such form and with such supporting documentation as required by the
Administrative Committee. Any expenditure greater than $25.00, for which a
reimbursement is requested, must be substantiated with a receipt. Where
expenditures are less than $25.00, receipts should be supplied when normally
available for the expense incurred. A proper accounting of the time, place, amount of
the expense, and any persons present is to be provided before reimbursement will be
7. Expenditures to be considered for reimbursement must be submitted to the
Administrative Committee within sixty (60) days following the last day on which the
expenditures were otherwise incurred, unless extenuating circumstances are present.
8. If a dispute arises concerning whether an expense reimbursement request conforms to
policy guidelines, Trust counsel should be consulted and, if necessary, the matter may
be referred to the Board of Trustees for a final determination.
Privately leased or owned automobile. If travel is by automobile, the
owner/lessee of the automobile shall be reimbursed for each mile actually
driven by the most direct route at the rate of 36.5 cents per mile (or such
other amount as the Internal Revenue Service may from time to time
authorize). Total reimbursement resulting from travel, including mileage,
lodging while in route, and/or actual automobile expenses shall not exceed
Other forms of travel: Modes of transportation other than by automobile
or air travel shall be reimbursable up to coach airfare allowance.
Car rental will be reimbursable where such rental is more economical that
the use of taxi or other means of transportation.
Actual cost of standard rate lodging. Laundry, movies, and other
incidental expenditures items of a personal nature shall not be
Cost of meals (including beverages and gratuities).
10. These guidelines shall be interpreted by the Trustees in a manner consistent with the
objectives of the Railroad Retirement and Survivors' Improvement Act of 2001 and
the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974.
11. The Trust's auditor shall be responsible for annual review of the expense
reimbursement practices of the Trust to insure consistency with these guidelines.
12. The Trustees may modify these reimbursement guidelines to reflect any change in
law, regulation, or other change in circumstance that is found to be necessary and
appropriate. The Trustees may waive the application of these rules in any instance
where such waiver is deemed to be necessary and appropriate, provided, however,
that notice of such waiver shall be recorded in the Minutes of the Board.

The National Railroad Retirement Investment Trust ("NRRIT") has enclosed its Form LM-10
Employer Report for FY 2004. It was only after the recent issuance of guidance by the Department of
Labor with respect to the reporting obligations of certain trusts that NRRIT became aware of a
possible obligation to report certain transactions relating to certain of its Trustees who are union
NRRIT was established pursuant to Section 105 of the Railroad Retirement Survivors'
Improvement Act of 2001 (Public Law 107-90) to manage the investment of the assets of Tier 2 of the
Federal government's railroad retirement system. While the Trust is not an agency or instrumentality
of the U.S. government, it also is not a "pension trust" as defined in ERISA. NRRIT is funded by
transfers of federal employment taxes from the Treasury. NRRIT is required by statute to make
periodic transfers back to the Treasury to fund certain benefit obligations of the railroad retirement
system. Since NRRIT assets are derived from Federal tax revenues and are held in trust to fund
benefits for an established Federal entitlement program, NRRIT assets are accounted for as part of the
Federal budget. As such, it remains unclear whether NRRIT should be considered an employer for
purposes of Form LM-10 reporting, or is more properly within the exception for the Federal
Under NRRIT's enabling statute, seven trustees are appointed to manage the Trust's operations.
The trustees receive reimbursement for travel, food and lodging expenses related to their participation
in NRRIT board meetings. Three of the current trustees are officers of rail labor organizations.
While NRRIT has made the decision to file a Form LM-10 report for FY 2004, we will be
seeking advice from the Office of Labor-Management Standards in the near future to determine
